{"title_page": "Two-front war", "text_new": "{{short description|Specific manifestation of warfare}}\n[[File:Ww2 allied axis 1940 may.png|thumb|right|375px|World map in May 1940, prior to the [[Battle of France]] with the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] in blue, the [[Axis Powers]] in black and the [[Communist International|Comintern]] [[Soviet Union]] and [[Mongolia]] in red. The Comintern joined the Allies in June 1941 upon the beginning of [[Operation Barbarossa]], thus confining Nazi Germany to fight a two-front war.]]\n\nAccording to [[military terminology]], a '''two-front war''' occurres, when opposing forces encounter on two geographically separate [[Front (military)|fronts]]. The forces of two or more allied parties usually simultaneously engage an opponent in order to increase their chances of success. The opponent consequently encounters severe logistic difficulties as he is forced to divide and disperse his troops, defend an extended front line and is at least partly cut off from access to trade and exterior resources. However, by virtue of the central position he might possess the advantages<ref name=\"Wasserstein2009\">{{cite book|author=Bernard Wasserstein|title=Barbarism and Civilization: A History of Europe in our Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XicFgasYzWQC&pg=PA45|date=12 February 2009|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-162251-9|pages=45\u2013}}</ref> of the [[interior lines]].<ref name=\"Nolan2002\">{{cite book|author=Cathal J. Nolan|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of International Relations: S-Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FMJ8KP8i3v0C&pg=PA1712|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-32383-6|pages=1712\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/interior-lines  |title= Interior Lines | publisher= Encyclopedia Com  | date=  | author= | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref>\n\nThe term has widely been used in a metaphorical sense, for example to illustrate the dilemma of military commanders in the field, who struggle to carry out illusory strategic ideas of civilian bureaucrats, or when [[Centrism|moderate]] legal motions or positions are concurrently opposed by the political [[Left-wing politics|Left]] and [[Right-wing politics|Right]].<ref name=\"Moon2012\">{{cite book|author=Joshua Moon|title=Wellington's Two-Front War: The Peninsular Campaigns, at Home and Abroad, 1808-1814|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gAxdkjB5aEC&pg=PA8|date=13 September 2012|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-8610-8|pages=8\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/03/trump-islam-authoritarianism/516627/ |title=America's Two-Front War of Ideas |publisher= The Atlantic Monthly Group   | date=March 3, 2017   | author=Uri Friedman  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref> Disapproval and opposition by the domestic [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|anti-war movement]] and [[Civil rights movement|civil rights]] groups as opposed to the bloody military struggle of the late [[Vietnam War]] has also been described as a two-front war for the US troops, who fought in Vietnam.<ref name=\"Eldridge2012\">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Allen Eldridge|title=Chronicles of a Two-Front War: Civil Rights and Vietnam in the African American Press|url=https://archive.org/details/chroniclesoftwof00eldr|url-access=registration|date=18 January 2012|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-7259-1}}</ref><ref name=\"FarrellTerriff2002\">{{cite book|author1=Theo Farrell|author2=Terry Terriff|title=The Sources of Military Change: Culture, Politics, Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYYlpMKnHNUC&pg=PA119|year=2002|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=978-1-55587-975-4|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Wars in antiquity==\nDuring the 5th-century BCE [[First Peloponnesian War]] the [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] [[polis]] of [[Classical Athens|Athens]] had been embroiled in a drawn out struggle with the poleis of [[Aegina]] and [[Corinth]] among others and its primary enemy [[Sparta]]. Aware of the dangers of a battle with the superior Spartans,  Athens concentrated on the conquest of [[Boeotia]] and thus avoid a prolonged two-front war.<ref name=\"Hanson2011\">{{cite book|author=Victor Davis Hanson|title=A War Like No Other: How the Athenians and Spartans Fought the Peloponnesian War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cZSgrIkkj_kC&pg=PA125|date=30 November 2011|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-58836-490-6|pages=125\u2013}}</ref>\n \nOn several occasions during the third century BCE, the [[Roman Republic]] engaged in two-front conflicts while clashing with the [[Gauls]] and [[Etruscans]] to the north and also campaigning in [[Magna Graecia]] (the coastal areas of Southern Italy). When Rome was enmeshed in the [[Second Punic War]] against [[Carthage]], [[Hannibal]], formal ally of the Sicilian city of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], intrigued with [[Philip V of Macedon]] in 215 BCE, who promptly declared [[First Macedonian War|war]] on Rome.<ref name=\"AndrewSalmon1967\">{{cite book|author1=Salmon, Julie Andrew|author2=E. T. Salmon|title=Samnium and the Samnites|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=boT6HtW5TCQC&pg=PA281|date=2 September 1967|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-06185-8|pages=281\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Carey2007\">{{cite book|author=Brian Todd Carey|title=Hannibal's Last Battle: Zama and the Fall of Carthage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M0JTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74|date=18 October 2007|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-84415-635-1|pages=74\u2013}}</ref> After the establishment of the [[Roman Empire]] and the consolidation of its frontiers under [[Augustus]], the Roman legions regularly battled multiple enemies, most notably Germanic tribes on the [[Rhine]] and the lower [[Danube]] and the [[Parthian Empire]] in Syria and [[Mesopotamia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/09/obama-two-front-war-rome-110779    |title= Don\u2019t Do As the Romans Did\u2026 | publisher= POLITICO LLC  | date= September 9, 2014 | author=Michael Auslin | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref> Various emperors, such as [[Septimius Severus]] and [[Aurelian]] forcibly lead large armies to the opposite ends of the empire in order to deal with the various threats. Beginning in the third century the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] - and its eastern successor the [[Byzantine Empire]], trying to preserve its [[Exarchate of Ravenna|territories in Italy]], struggled with the [[Sassanid Empire]] to the east for a period of more than 400 years. Large-scale incursions of Germanic tribes, such as the Goths and Hunnic raids in the west began during the fouth century and lasted for more than a hundred years.<ref name=\"Heather2005\">{{cite book|author=Peter Heather|title=The Fall of the Roman Empire: A New History of Rome and the Barbarians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCOJfTB7HtgC|date=28 October 2005|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-515954-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transoxiana.com.ar/0104/sasanians.html |title=Transoxiana 04: Sasanians in Africa |publisher=Transoxiana.com.ar |accessdate=May 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Seven Years' War==\nThe [[French and Indian War]] was a local conflict in North America, that occurred in the context of the trans-continental [[Seven Years' War]]. In 1755 armed forces of [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]] under the command of General [[Edward Braddock]] [[Battle of the Monongahela|invaded]] the territories of [[New France]] (eastern part of modern Canada) and attacked [[Fort Duquesne]]. Although numerically superior to the local French militia and their Indian allies, the British army became ensnared in a two-front conflict and was routed.<ref>{{cite book |first=Fred |last=Anderson |title=Crucible of War: The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North America, 1754\u20131766 |year=2000 |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |pages=[https://archive.org/details/crucibleofwarsev00ande_0/page/15] |isbn=0375406425 |url=https://archive.org/details/crucibleofwarsev00ande_0/page/15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wdl.org/en/item/9580/    |title= The Battle of the Monongahela  | publisher=  WDL  | date=  | author=  | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n==Napoleonic Wars==\nDuring the [[Napoleonic Wars]], France repeatedly fought on multiple fronts.  For example, France fought the [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[Anglo-Portuguese Army|Anglo-Portuguese army]] in the [[Peninsular War]] while fighting the [[Russian Empire]] at the same time during its [[French invasion of Russia|invasion of Russia]].<ref name=\"Hui2005\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Tin-bor Hui|title=War and State Formation in Ancient China and Early Modern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M5Wvw2i84DAC&pg=PA135|date=4 July 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-44356-2|pages=135\u2013}}</ref> Their main adversaries the British were also engaged on multiple fronts at various times, having also to contend with the [[United States]] starting with the [[War of 1812]] in [[Canada]], the [[Chesapeake Bay]], and [[Louisiana]].\n\n==World War I==\nDuring [[World War I]], the [[German Empire|Germany]] and [[Austria-Hungary]] fought two-front wars against France, Great Britain, Italy, Belgium and later also American forces on their respective [[Western Front (World War I)|Western]] and [[Italian front (World War I)|Alpine]] fronts and Russia and later Romania on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]]. Russian participation in the war ended with the 1917 [[October Revolution|Bolshevik October Coup]] and the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk|peace treaty]] with Germany and Austria-Hungary was signed in March 1918. German military strategists had conceived such a scenario, and developed the [[Schlieffen Plan]] in order to counteract being surrounded by its enemies.<ref name=\"EhlertEpkenhans2014\">{{cite book|author=Hans Ehlert, Michael Epkenhans, Gerhard P. Gross, David T. Zabecki|title=The Schlieffen Plan: International Perspectives on the German Strategy for World War I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IVjCBAAAQBAJ|date=14 October 2014|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-4747-5}}</ref> Under the Schlieffen Plan, German forces would invade France via [[Belgium]], [[Luxembourg]], and the [[Netherlands]] (the idea to go through the Netherlands was abandoned because of the [[The Netherlands in World War I|country's neutrality]]), quickly capturing [[Paris]] and forcing France to sue for peace. The Germans would then turn their attention to the East before the Russian army could [[Mobilization|mobilize]] its massive forces. The Germans failed to achieve the plan's objectives.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/germany-could-have-won-world-war-i-heres-how-35882  |title=Germany Could Have Won World War I. Here's How. |publisher= Center for the National Interest   | date=November 11, 2018   | author=Michael Peck  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts2009\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Roberts|title=The Storm of War: A New History of the Second World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZC-IBqQitdsC&pg=PR173|date=6 August 2009|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-193886-8|pages=173\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Zuber2002\">{{cite book|author=Terence Zuber|title=Inventing the Schlieffen Plan: German War Planning 1871-1914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yuDVsT6JvtsC|date=31 October 2002|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-164771-0}}</ref>\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:1944-12-15GerWW2BattlefrontAtlas.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Map of remaining German-controlled territory (in white) on December 15, 1944.]]\n\nA two-front war scenario, almost identical to the first World War would eventually aggregate in the [[European Theatre of World War II|European theatre]] during [[World War II]], when [[Nazi Germany]] confronted [[Allies of World War II|allied]] France, Great Britain, Belgium, the Netherlands and later the United States in the west and the [[Soviet Union]] to the east.<ref name=\"Harrison2010\">{{cite book|author=Richard W. Harrison|title=Architect of Soviet Victory in World War II: The Life and Theories of G.S. Isserson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C17uxAfGKdIC&pg=PA216|date=13 April 2010 | publisher=McFarland | isbn=978-0-7864-5667-3 |pages=216\u2013}}</ref> Germany, that lacked the resources for a long war, failed to achieve a quick victory in the east and eventually collapsed under the pressure of a [[Attrition warfare|war of attrition]] on two fronts, accelerated by a surge of resistance and partisan groups in virtually all occupied countries. Reduced production output and dwindling replacements of casualties as a consequence of massive material warfare and [[Strategic bombing during World War II|Allied strategic bombing]] and shortages in [[Oil Campaign of World War II|fuel]] and raw materials increasingly prevented the continuation of German offensive - and [[Blitzkrieg|Blitzkrieg tactics]]. In contrast, steadily improving Allied cooperative warfare, based on an exponentially growing war industry brought about the inevitable total military defeat for Germany.<ref name=\"Chandonnet2007\">{{cite book|author=Fern Chandonnet|title=Alaska at War, 1941-1945: The Forgotten War Remembered|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p01bFVagOJYC&pg=PA345|date=15 September 2007|publisher=University of Alaska Press|isbn=978-1-60223-135-1|pages=345\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://classroom.synonym.com/effects-twofront-war-germany-during-wwii-22440.html  |title=The Effects of the Two-Front War on Germany During WWII |publisher= Leaf Group Ltd  | date=  | author=Jeffrey Billman  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://academic.oup.com/ahr/article-abstract/72/3/965/55216?redirectedFrom=fulltext  |title=Hitler And Russia: The Third Reich in a Two-Front War, 1937\u20131943 |publisher= Oxford University Press  | date=April 1, 1967  | author=Higgins Trumbull  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Baker2013\">{{cite book|author=Lee Baker|title=The Second World War on the Eastern Front|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fYraAAAAQBAJ&pg=PR34|date=13 September 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-86504-9|pages=34\u2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States]], who had, since December 1941, primarily focused on the conflict with the [[Japanese Empire]], eventually established an Atlantic front in order to support their European allies, beginning in November 1942 with an [[Operation Torch|amphibious landing]] in North Africa, later to continue the campaign in Sicily and on the Italian peninsula and invade France on the beaches of Normandy in 1944.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.army.mil/books/70-7_07.htm    |title= The Decision To Invade North Africa (TORCH) | publisher= U.S. Army Center of Military History  | date=  | author=Leo J. Meyer  | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref><ref name=\"Axelrod2008\">{{cite book|author=Alan Axelrod|title=The Real History of World War II: A New Look at the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqYWmUae5h8C&pg=PA144|year=2008|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4027-4090-9|pages=179\u2013}}</ref> Their colossal military strength and favorable strategic position in between two oceans without territorial borders to any of the Axis powers allowed the US forces to safely wage an offensive two-front war by maintaining the initiative in the [[Pacific War]], contain and defeat Japan and also increase American presence in European that ensures Allied victory over Nazi Germany.<ref name=\"Morton2014\">{{cite book|author=Professor Louis Morton|title=United States Army in WWII - the Pacific - Strategy and Command - Part three: Seizing the initiative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pIBvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|date=15 August 2014|publisher=Verdun Press|isbn=978-1-78289-397-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Klein2013\">{{cite book|author=Maury Klein|title=A Call to Arms: Mobilizing America for World War II \u00b4The feasibility follies, p. 377 -|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lolBMB5rXI8C|date=16 July 2013|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-60819-409-4}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Axis Powers]] had the opportunity to force the Soviet Union into a two-front war by means of a Japanese attack on the [[Soviet Far East]], but the Japanese decided against doing so because of their defeats in the [[Soviet\u2013Japanese border conflicts]]. While Germany and the United States remained respective threats, the Soviets and Japanese did not fight each another until the 9 August [[Soviet\u2013Japanese War]], three months after the surrender of Germany. Japan thus fought a two-front war as well and split its forces between China in the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] and the United States in the Pacific Theatre. The Soviet Union later invaded Manchuria, worsening the situation for Japan.<ref name=\"Addington1994\">{{cite book|author=Larry H. Addington|title=The Patterns of War Since the Eighteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=313YB9VXIVAC&pg=PT303|date=22 October 1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0-253-11109-8|pages=303\u2013}}</ref>\n<!-- UNCLEAR: \nIn the case of the United States, the Pacific Theatre was primarily a naval and air effort despite losing ships during the 1941 [[Pearl Harbor Attack]] while the majority of the ground forces were used in Europe. Likewise for Japan, most ground troops were fighting China, and the Pacific Theatre was also primarily a naval and aerial battle. It was also the first time the United States ever fought a two-front war.-->\n\n==Cold War==\nA major rationale for the American [[600-ship Navy]] plan in the 1980s was to threaten the Soviet Union with a two-front war, in Europe and the Pacific Ocean, in the event of hostilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/scn-1981-reagan.htm  |title= Ship Building 1981-89 - Reagan, Ronald | publisher= Global Security  | date=  | author= | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n===Israeli-Arab Wars===\nIn the [[1948 Israeli-Arab War]], the Israelis fought the [[Egypt]]ians to the south and the [[Jordan]]ians and [[Syria]]ns in the east and the north. Israel again fought two-front wars in the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967 and the [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973.<ref name=\"Aker2014\">{{cite book|author=Frank Aker|title=October 1973 The Arab Israeli War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G38BBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT20|date=22 October 2014|publisher=First Edition Design Pub.|isbn=978-1-62287-755-3|pages=20\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Rabinovich2007\">{{cite book|author=Abraham Rabinovich|title=The Yom Kippur War: The Epic Encounter That Transformed the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_9gIR6Fi3UC|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42965-0}}</ref><ref name=\"HarkavyNeuman2016\">{{cite book|author1=R. Harkavy|author2=S. Neuman|title=Warfare and the Third World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NeQYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA95|date=30 April 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-1-137-07926-8|pages=95\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n[[Category:Military strategy]]\n[[Category:Warfare by type]]\n[[Category:Military science]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Specific manifestation of warfare}}\n[[File:Ww2 allied axis 1940 may.png|thumb|right|375px|World map in May 1940, prior to the [[Battle of France]] with the [[Allies of World War II|Western Allies]] in blue, the [[Axis Powers]] in black and the [[Communist International|Comintern]] [[Soviet Union]] and [[Mongolia]] in red. The Comintern joined the Allies in June 1941 upon the beginning of [[Operation Barbarossa]], thus confining Nazi Germany to fight a two-front war.]]\n\nAccording to [[military terminology]], a '''two-front war''' occurres, when opposing forces encounter on two geographically separate [[Front (military)|fronts]]. The forces of two or more allied parties usually simultaneously engage an opponent in order to increase their chances of success. The opponent consequently encounters severe logistic difficulties as he is forced to divide and disperse his troops, defend an extended front line and is at least partly cut off from access to trade and exterior resources. However, by virtue of the central position he might possess the advantages<ref name=\"Wasserstein2009\">{{cite book|author=Bernard Wasserstein|title=Barbarism and Civilization: A History of Europe in our Time|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XicFgasYzWQC&pg=PA45|date=12 February 2009|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-162251-9|pages=45\u2013}}</ref> of the [[interior lines]].<ref name=\"Nolan2002\">{{cite book|author=Cathal J. Nolan|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of International Relations: S-Z|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FMJ8KP8i3v0C&pg=PA1712|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-32383-6|pages=1712\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/interior-lines  |title= Interior Lines | publisher= Encyclopedia Com  | date=  | author= | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref>\n\nThe term has widely been used in a metaphorical sense, for example to illustrate the dilemma of military commanders in the field, who struggle to carry out illusory strategic ideas of civilian bureaucrats, or when [[Centrism|moderate]] legal motions or positions are concurrently opposed by the political [[Left-wing politics|Left]] and [[Right-wing politics|Right]].<ref name=\"Moon2012\">{{cite book|author=Joshua Moon|title=Wellington's Two-Front War: The Peninsular Campaigns, at Home and Abroad, 1808-1814|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4gAxdkjB5aEC&pg=PA8|date=13 September 2012|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-8061-8610-8|pages=8\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/03/trump-islam-authoritarianism/516627/ |title=America's Two-Front War of Ideas |publisher= The Atlantic Monthly Group   | date=March 3, 2017   | author=Uri Friedman  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref> Disapproval and opposition by the domestic [[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War|anti-war movement]] and [[Civil rights movement|civil rights]] groups as opposed to the bloody military struggle of the late [[Vietnam War]] has also been described as a two-front war for the US troops, who fought in Vietnam.<ref name=\"Eldridge2012\">{{cite book|author=Lawrence Allen Eldridge|title=Chronicles of a Two-Front War: Civil Rights and Vietnam in the African American Press|url=https://archive.org/details/chroniclesoftwof00eldr|url-access=registration|date=18 January 2012|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-7259-1}}</ref><ref name=\"FarrellTerriff2002\">{{cite book|author1=Theo Farrell|author2=Terry Terriff|title=The Sources of Military Change: Culture, Politics, Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IYYlpMKnHNUC&pg=PA119|year=2002|publisher=Lynne Rienner Publishers|isbn=978-1-55587-975-4|pages=119\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==Wars in antiquity==\nDuring the 5th-century BCE [[First Peloponnesian War]] the [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] [[polis]] of [[Classical Athens|Athens]] had been embroiled in a drawn out struggle with the poleis of [[Aegina]] and [[Corinth]] among others and its primary enemy [[Sparta]]. Aware of the dangers of a battle with the superior Spartans,  Athens concentrated on the conquest of [[Boeotia]] and thus avoid a prolonged two-front war.<ref name=\"Hanson2011\">{{cite book|author=Victor Davis Hanson|title=A War Like No Other: How the Athenians and Spartans Fought the Peloponnesian War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cZSgrIkkj_kC&pg=PA125|date=30 November 2011|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-58836-490-6|pages=125\u2013}}</ref>\n \nOn several occasions during the third century BCE, the [[Roman Republic]] engaged in two-front conflicts while clashing with the [[Gauls]] and [[Etruscans]] to the north and also campaigning in [[Magna Graecia]] (the coastal areas of Southern Italy). When Rome was enmeshed in the [[Second Punic War]] against [[Carthage]], [[Hannibal]], formal ally of the Sicilian city of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], intrigued with [[Philip V of Macedon]] in 215 BCE, who promptly declared [[First Macedonian War|war]] on Rome.<ref name=\"AndrewSalmon1967\">{{cite book|author1=Salmon, Julie Andrew|author2=E. T. Salmon|title=Samnium and the Samnites|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=boT6HtW5TCQC&pg=PA281|date=2 September 1967|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-06185-8|pages=281\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Carey2007\">{{cite book|author=Brian Todd Carey|title=Hannibal's Last Battle: Zama and the Fall of Carthage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M0JTAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74|date=18 October 2007|publisher=Pen and Sword|isbn=978-1-84415-635-1|pages=74\u2013}}</ref> After the establishment of the [[Roman Empire]] and the consolidation of its frontiers under [[Augustus]], the Roman legions regularly battled multiple enemies, most notably Germanic tribes on the [[Rhine]] and the lower [[Danube]] and the [[Parthian Empire]] in Syria and [[Mesopotamia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/09/obama-two-front-war-rome-110779    |title= Don\u2019t Do As the Romans Did\u2026 | publisher= POLITICO LLC  | date= September 9, 2014 | author=Michael Auslin | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref> Various emperors, such as [[Septimius Severus]] and [[Aurelian]] forcibly lead large armies to the opposite ends of the empire in order to deal with the various threats. Beginning in the third century the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] - and its eastern successor the [[Byzantine Empire]], trying to preserve its [[Exarchate of Ravenna|territories in Italy]], struggled with the [[Sassanid Empire]] to the east for a period of more than 400 years. Large-scale incursions of Germanic tribes, such as the Goths and Hunnic raids in the west began during the fouth century and lasted for more than a hundred years.<ref name=\"Heather2005\">{{cite book|author=Peter Heather|title=The Fall of the Roman Empire: A New History of Rome and the Barbarians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCOJfTB7HtgC|date=28 October 2005|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-515954-7}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transoxiana.com.ar/0104/sasanians.html |title=Transoxiana 04: Sasanians in Africa |publisher=Transoxiana.com.ar |accessdate=May 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Seven Years' War==\nDuring the [[Seven Years' War]], the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] [[French and Indian War|invaded]] [[New France]], creating a two-front war with France.<ref>{{cite book |first=Fred |last=Anderson |title=Crucible of War: The Seven Years' War and the Fate of Empire in British North America, 1754\u20131766 |year=2000 |location=New York |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf |pages=[https://archive.org/details/crucibleofwarsev00ande_0/page/15] |isbn=0375406425 |url=https://archive.org/details/crucibleofwarsev00ande_0/page/15 }}</ref>\n\n==Napoleonic Wars==\nDuring the [[Napoleonic Wars]], France repeatedly fought on multiple fronts.  For example, France fought the [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[Anglo-Portuguese Army|Anglo-Portuguese army]] in the [[Peninsular War]] while fighting the [[Russian Empire]] at the same time during its [[French invasion of Russia|invasion of Russia]].<ref name=\"Hui2005\">{{cite book|author=Victoria Tin-bor Hui|title=War and State Formation in Ancient China and Early Modern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M5Wvw2i84DAC&pg=PA135|date=4 July 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-44356-2|pages=135\u2013}}</ref> Their main adversaries the British were also engaged on multiple fronts at various times, having also to contend with the [[United States]] starting with the [[War of 1812]] in [[Canada]], the [[Chesapeake Bay]], and [[Louisiana]].\n\n==World War I==\nDuring [[World War I]], the [[German Empire|Germany]] and [[Austria-Hungary]] fought two-front wars against France, Great Britain, Italy, Belgium and later also American forces on their respective [[Western Front (World War I)|Western]] and [[Italian front (World War I)|Alpine]] fronts and Russia and later Romania on the [[Eastern Front (World War I)|Eastern Front]]. Russian participation in the war ended with the 1917 [[October Revolution|Bolshevik October Coup]] and the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk|peace treaty]] with Germany and Austria-Hungary was signed in March 1918. German military strategists had conceived such a scenario, and developed the [[Schlieffen Plan]] in order to counteract being surrounded by its enemies.<ref name=\"EhlertEpkenhans2014\">{{cite book|author=Hans Ehlert, Michael Epkenhans, Gerhard P. Gross, David T. Zabecki|title=The Schlieffen Plan: International Perspectives on the German Strategy for World War I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IVjCBAAAQBAJ|date=14 October 2014|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=978-0-8131-4747-5}}</ref> Under the Schlieffen Plan, German forces would invade France via [[Belgium]], [[Luxembourg]], and the [[Netherlands]] (the idea to go through the Netherlands was abandoned because of the [[The Netherlands in World War I|country's neutrality]]), quickly capturing [[Paris]] and forcing France to sue for peace. The Germans would then turn their attention to the East before the Russian army could [[Mobilization|mobilize]] its massive forces. The Germans failed to achieve the plan's objectives.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/germany-could-have-won-world-war-i-heres-how-35882  |title=Germany Could Have Won World War I. Here's How. |publisher= Center for the National Interest   | date=November 11, 2018   | author=Michael Peck  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Roberts2009\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Roberts|title=The Storm of War: A New History of the Second World War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZC-IBqQitdsC&pg=PR173|date=6 August 2009|publisher=Penguin Books Limited|isbn=978-0-14-193886-8|pages=173\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Zuber2002\">{{cite book|author=Terence Zuber|title=Inventing the Schlieffen Plan: German War Planning 1871-1914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yuDVsT6JvtsC|date=31 October 2002|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-164771-0}}</ref>\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:1944-12-15GerWW2BattlefrontAtlas.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Map of remaining German-controlled territory (in white) on December 15, 1944.]]\n\nA two-front war scenario, almost identical to the first World War would eventually aggregate in the [[European Theatre of World War II|European theatre]] during [[World War II]], when [[Nazi Germany]] confronted [[Allies of World War II|allied]] France, Great Britain, Belgium, the Netherlands and later the United States in the west and the [[Soviet Union]] to the east.<ref name=\"Harrison2010\">{{cite book|author=Richard W. Harrison|title=Architect of Soviet Victory in World War II: The Life and Theories of G.S. Isserson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C17uxAfGKdIC&pg=PA216|date=13 April 2010 | publisher=McFarland | isbn=978-0-7864-5667-3 |pages=216\u2013}}</ref> Germany, that lacked the resources for a long war, failed to achieve a quick victory in the east and eventually collapsed under the pressure of a [[Attrition warfare|war of attrition]] on two fronts, accelerated by a surge of resistance and partisan groups in virtually all occupied countries. Reduced production output and dwindling replacements of casualties as a consequence of massive material warfare and [[Strategic bombing during World War II|Allied strategic bombing]] and shortages in [[Oil Campaign of World War II|fuel]] and raw materials increasingly prevented the continuation of German offensive - and [[Blitzkrieg|Blitzkrieg tactics]]. In contrast, steadily improving Allied cooperative warfare, based on an exponentially growing war industry brought about the inevitable total military defeat for Germany.<ref name=\"Chandonnet2007\">{{cite book|author=Fern Chandonnet|title=Alaska at War, 1941-1945: The Forgotten War Remembered|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p01bFVagOJYC&pg=PA345|date=15 September 2007|publisher=University of Alaska Press|isbn=978-1-60223-135-1|pages=345\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://classroom.synonym.com/effects-twofront-war-germany-during-wwii-22440.html  |title=The Effects of the Two-Front War on Germany During WWII |publisher= Leaf Group Ltd  | date=  | author=Jeffrey Billman  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://academic.oup.com/ahr/article-abstract/72/3/965/55216?redirectedFrom=fulltext  |title=Hitler And Russia: The Third Reich in a Two-Front War, 1937\u20131943 |publisher= Oxford University Press  | date=April 1, 1967  | author=Higgins Trumbull  | accessdate= May 19, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"Baker2013\">{{cite book|author=Lee Baker|title=The Second World War on the Eastern Front|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fYraAAAAQBAJ&pg=PR34|date=13 September 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-86504-9|pages=34\u2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States]], who had, since December 1941, primarily focused on the conflict with the [[Japanese Empire]], eventually established an Atlantic front in order to support their European allies, beginning in November 1942 with an [[Operation Torch|amphibious landing]] in North Africa, later to continue the campaign in Sicily and on the Italian peninsula and invade France on the beaches of Normandy in 1944.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://history.army.mil/books/70-7_07.htm    |title= The Decision To Invade North Africa (TORCH) | publisher= U.S. Army Center of Military History  | date=  | author=Leo J. Meyer  | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref><ref name=\"Axelrod2008\">{{cite book|author=Alan Axelrod|title=The Real History of World War II: A New Look at the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqYWmUae5h8C&pg=PA144|year=2008|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4027-4090-9|pages=179\u2013}}</ref> Their colossal military strength and favorable strategic position in between two oceans without territorial borders to any of the Axis powers allowed the US forces to safely wage an offensive two-front war by maintaining the initiative in the [[Pacific War]], contain and defeat Japan and also increase American presence in European that ensures Allied victory over Nazi Germany.<ref name=\"Morton2014\">{{cite book|author=Professor Louis Morton|title=United States Army in WWII - the Pacific - Strategy and Command - Part three: Seizing the initiative|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pIBvCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT42|date=15 August 2014|publisher=Verdun Press|isbn=978-1-78289-397-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Klein2013\">{{cite book|author=Maury Klein|title=A Call to Arms: Mobilizing America for World War II \u00b4The feasibility follies, p. 377 -|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lolBMB5rXI8C|date=16 July 2013|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-60819-409-4}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Axis Powers]] had the opportunity to force the Soviet Union into a two-front war by means of a Japanese attack on the [[Soviet Far East]], but the Japanese decided against doing so because of their defeats in the [[Soviet\u2013Japanese border conflicts]]. While Germany and the United States remained respective threats, the Soviets and Japanese did not fight each another until the 9 August [[Soviet\u2013Japanese War]], three months after the surrender of Germany. Japan thus fought a two-front war as well and split its forces between China in the [[Second Sino-Japanese War]] and the United States in the Pacific Theatre. The Soviet Union later invaded Manchuria, worsening the situation for Japan.<ref name=\"Addington1994\">{{cite book|author=Larry H. Addington|title=The Patterns of War Since the Eighteenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=313YB9VXIVAC&pg=PT303|date=22 October 1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0-253-11109-8|pages=303\u2013}}</ref>\n<!-- UNCLEAR: \nIn the case of the United States, the Pacific Theatre was primarily a naval and air effort despite losing ships during the 1941 [[Pearl Harbor Attack]] while the majority of the ground forces were used in Europe. Likewise for Japan, most ground troops were fighting China, and the Pacific Theatre was also primarily a naval and aerial battle. It was also the first time the United States ever fought a two-front war.-->\n\n==Cold War==\nA major rationale for the American [[600-ship Navy]] plan in the 1980s was to threaten the Soviet Union with a two-front war, in Europe and the Pacific Ocean, in the event of hostilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ship/scn-1981-reagan.htm  |title= Ship Building 1981-89 - Reagan, Ronald | publisher= Global Security  | date=  | author= | accessdate= May 1, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n===Israeli-Arab Wars===\nIn the [[1948 Israeli-Arab War]], the Israelis fought the [[Egypt]]ians to the south and the [[Jordan]]ians and [[Syria]]ns in the east and the north. Israel again fought two-front wars in the [[Six-Day War]] of 1967 and the [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973.<ref name=\"Aker2014\">{{cite book|author=Frank Aker|title=October 1973 The Arab Israeli War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G38BBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT20|date=22 October 2014|publisher=First Edition Design Pub.|isbn=978-1-62287-755-3|pages=20\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Rabinovich2007\">{{cite book|author=Abraham Rabinovich|title=The Yom Kippur War: The Epic Encounter That Transformed the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n_9gIR6Fi3UC|date=18 December 2007|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-42965-0}}</ref><ref name=\"HarkavyNeuman2016\">{{cite book|author1=R. Harkavy|author2=S. Neuman|title=Warfare and the Third World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NeQYDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA95|date=30 April 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-1-137-07926-8|pages=95\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n[[Category:Military strategy]]\n[[Category:Warfare by type]]\n[[Category:Military science]]\n", "name_user": "Wikirictor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeven Years' War", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-front_war"}
